    <h1 class="title">Petra: The Rose City</h1>
    
    <section>
        <h2 class="section-title">
            History
        </h2>

        <p>
            Petra, once the thriving capital of the Nabataean Kingdom, dates back to the 4th century BC. The Nabataeans, a nomadic Arab people, settled in the area and transformed it into a hub of trade and culture. Petra’s strategic location at the intersection of several ancient trade routes allowed it to flourish as a center for commerce, particularly in spices, incense, and precious metals. By the time of its peak, Petra was known for its advanced water systems and impressive rock-cut architecture, making it one of the most remarkable cities of the ancient world.
            <br>
            Over time, the city grew under the rule of Nabataean kings, with the most prosperous period occurring during the reign of King Aretas IV in the 1st century AD, when Petra became an essential stop on trade routes between Arabia, Egypt, and the Mediterranean.
            <img src="\img\petra_history.jpg" />
        </p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2 class="section-title">
            Architectural Wonders
        </h2>

        <p>
            Petra is world-renowned for its stunning rock-cut architecture, with buildings carved directly into the vibrant red sandstone cliffs. The city’s most famous structure, Al-Khazneh (the Treasury), is a majestic façade carved into a canyon wall. Petra’s inhabitants also created intricate tombs, temples, and amphitheaters, blending local traditions with Hellenistic and Roman influences. The architecture wasn’t just for show; the Nabataeans ingeniously built extensive water management systems, including cisterns, channels, and aqueducts, to ensure the city’s survival in the desert. 
            <br>
            These innovations enabled Petra to support a large population despite its arid location, and they showcase the city’s remarkable engineering expertise.
            <img src="\img\petra_architecture.jpg" />
        </p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2 class="section-title">
            Role in Trade and Culture
        </h2>

        <p>
            As a key player in ancient trade, Petra was more than just a city; it was a melting pot of cultures. The city’s location allowed it to become an essential center for trade, where goods such as frankincense, myrrh, and silk were exchanged. Petra’s markets were bustling with merchants and traders from across the ancient world, and the city became a symbol of wealth and prosperity. 
            <br>
            In addition to its commercial role, Petra was also a cultural center, where the blending of Eastern and Western traditions can be seen in its art, architecture, and religious practices. The Nabataeans developed a unique form of writing and created intricate carvings and reliefs that told stories of their gods, kings, and daily life.
            <img src="\img\petra_trade.jpg" />
        </p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2 class="section-title">
            Petra’s Decline and Rediscovery
        </h2>

        <p>
            Petra’s decline began after the Roman Empire annexed the Nabataean Kingdom in 106 AD, marking the beginning of a slow but steady downfall. Natural disasters, such as earthquakes, and the shift of trade routes away from the region contributed to the city’s eventual abandonment. By the 7th century, Petra had largely fallen into ruin and was forgotten by most of the world.
            <br>
            The city remained hidden from the Western world until it was rediscovered in 1812 by Swiss explorer Johann Ludwig Burckhardt. Despite its rediscovery, Petra remained largely unstudied for decades, and it wasn't until the 20th century that serious archaeological efforts began to uncover the city’s history and its remarkable achievements.
            <img src="\img\petra_decline.jpg" />
        </p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2 class="section-title">
            Petra Today
        </h2>

        <p>
            Today, Petra stands as a testament to the ingenuity and perseverance of the Nabataeans. The city’s rock-cut structures and water management systems continue to amaze visitors from around the world. Though some areas have fallen into disrepair, restoration and preservation efforts are ongoing to protect Petra’s fragile monuments. 
            <br>
            As an archaeological site, Petra is an invaluable source of knowledge about ancient cultures and civilizations. Its unique blend of architectural and engineering feats provides important insights into the capabilities of the ancient world and continues to inspire awe in all who visit.
            <!-- <img src="\img\petra_today.jpg" /> -->
        </p>
    </section>

